---
import SiteLayout from "../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";

const schema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": ["Article", "FAQPage"],
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How do you calculate profit on an options call?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "For a long call option, your profit at expiration is calculated by taking the underlying stock price, subtracting the strike price, and then subtracting the premium paid. Multiply this result by 100 per contract. If the stock price is below the strike price, your loss is capped at the premium paid."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How do you use an options profit calculator?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "To use an options profit calculator, enter your option's strike price, the premium paid (or received), the expiration date, and the number of contracts. The calculator will automatically generate a payoff diagram showing your break-even point, maximum profit, and maximum loss."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is a good payoff for options?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "A good payoff for options depends on your risk tolerance and strategy. Many traders look for a risk-to-reward ratio of at least 1:2 or 1:3, meaning they aim to make $2 or $3 for every $1 they risk. For selling options, a good payoff might mean consistently collecting premium with a high probability of success."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How do you calculate break even on a put option?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "To calculate the break-even point for a long put option, subtract the premium paid from the strike price. For a short put option (selling a put), the break-even point is also the strike price minus the premium received."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Can you lose more than you invest in options?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes, but it depends on the strategy. If you buy options (long calls or long puts), your maximum loss is strictly limited to the premium paid. However, if you sell naked options (short calls or short puts), your risk can be substantial, and in the case of naked short calls, theoretically unlimited."
      }
    }
  ]
};

export const meta = {
  title: "Options Profit Calculator: Calls, Puts & Spreads Payoff",
  description: "Visualize options strategies with our advanced options profit calculator. Model multi-leg strategies to find exact break-evens and max profit—what are you risking?",
  category: "tool",
  published: "2026-03-15",
};
---

<SiteLayout
  site="westmount"
  title="Options Profit Calculator: Calls, Puts & Spreads Payoff"
  description="Visualize options strategies with our advanced options profit calculator. Model multi-leg strategies to find exact break-evens and max profit—what are you risking?"
  canonical="https://westmountfundamentals.com/options-profit-calculator"
  schema={schema}
>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>Options Profit Calculator</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">Model multi-leg options strategies, calculate max profit/loss, and visualize your exact payoff at expiration.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="calculator-container">
      <div class="calculator-grid">
        <!-- Left Column: Inputs -->
        <div class="calc-panel">
          <h3 style="margin-bottom: 1rem;">Option Legs</h3>
          <div id="legs-container"></div>
          <button id="add-leg-btn" class="btn-secondary">+ Add Leg</button>
        </div>

        <!-- Right Column: Results & Chart -->
        <div class="calc-panel">
          <div class="stats-grid">
            <div class="stat-box">
              <div class="stat-label">Max Profit</div>
              <div class="stat-value" id="stat-max-profit">--</div>
            </div>
            <div class="stat-box">
              <div class="stat-label">Max Loss</div>
              <div class="stat-value" id="stat-max-loss">--</div>
            </div>
            <div class="stat-box">
              <div class="stat-label">Break-even(s)</div>
              <div class="stat-value break-even-val" id="stat-break-even">--</div>
            </div>
            <div class="stat-box">
              <div class="stat-label">Net Premium</div>
              <div class="stat-value" id="stat-net-premium">--</div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="chart-wrapper">
            <canvas id="payoffChart"></canvas>
          </div>

          <div class="table-container mt-4">
            <table id="pnl-table">
              <thead>
                <tr>
                  <th>Underlying Price</th>
                  <th>Profit / Loss</th>
                  <th>Return on Risk</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody id="pnl-tbody"></tbody>
            </table>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="explainer">
      <h2>Comprehensive Options Pricing Methodology</h2>
      <p>Understanding the precise risk and reward profile of an options trade is critical before entering any position. This options profit calculator utilizes intrinsic value modeling at expiration to generate theoretical payoff diagrams. It supports complex, multi-leg strategies by aggregating the individual payoffs of each leg into a single net profit and loss (P&L) curve.</p>

      <p>If you are also trading the underlying equities, it is highly recommended to combine your options analysis with our <a href="/position-size-calculator">Position Size Calculator</a> to ensure your overall portfolio risk remains within acceptable limits.</p>

      <h3>The Core Options Mechanics: Calls and Puts</h3>
      <p>Options contracts are derivatives, meaning their value is derived from the price of an underlying asset. Standard equity options contracts typically represent 100 shares of the underlying stock. There are two primary types of options: calls and puts.</p>

      <p><strong>Call Options:</strong> A call option gives the buyer the right, but not the obligation, to buy the underlying stock at a specified strike price before the expiration date. Buyers of call options are generally bullish, expecting the stock price to rise. Sellers (writers) of call options take on the obligation to sell the stock at the strike price if assigned. Sellers are generally neutral to bearish, or they may be writing covered calls against an existing stock position to generate income.</p>

      <p><strong>Put Options:</strong> A put option gives the buyer the right, but not the obligation, to sell the underlying stock at a specified strike price. Buyers of put options are generally bearish, expecting the stock price to fall. They can also be used as a form of insurance (protective puts) to hedge an existing long stock position against downside risk. Sellers of put options take on the obligation to buy the stock at the strike price if assigned, typically expressing a neutral to bullish view, often with the intention of acquiring the stock at a discount while collecting premium.</p>

      <h3>Calculating Option Payoffs at Expiration</h3>
      <p>This calculator specifically models the payoff at expiration. At expiration, the time value component of an option's premium decays to zero, leaving only its intrinsic value. The intrinsic value calculations are absolute and mathematically defined:</p>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>Long Call Payoff:</strong> <code>Max(0, Underlying Price - Strike Price) - Premium Paid</code>. The maximum loss is limited to the premium paid, while the theoretical maximum profit is unlimited as the stock price can rise indefinitely.</li>
        <li><strong>Short Call Payoff:</strong> <code>Premium Received - Max(0, Underlying Price - Strike Price)</code>. The maximum profit is capped at the premium received. If the call is "naked" (uncovered), the theoretical maximum loss is unlimited.</li>
        <li><strong>Long Put Payoff:</strong> <code>Max(0, Strike Price - Underlying Price) - Premium Paid</code>. The maximum loss is limited to the premium paid. The maximum profit occurs if the underlying stock goes to zero, yielding <code>Strike Price - Premium Paid</code>.</li>
        <li><strong>Short Put Payoff:</strong> <code>Premium Received - Max(0, Strike Price - Underlying Price)</code>. The maximum profit is capped at the premium received, while the maximum loss occurs if the stock goes to zero, resulting in a loss of <code>Strike Price - Premium Received</code>.</li>
      </ul>

      <p>To determine the total strategy payoff, the calculator computes the intrinsic value of each leg independently at various underlying price intervals. It then sums these individual payoffs, factoring in the number of contracts and the standard 100x multiplier, to construct the net P&L curve visualized in the payoff diagram.</p>

      <h3>Advanced Multi-Leg Strategies</h3>
      <p>By combining multiple calls and puts at different strikes and expirations, traders can construct strategies tailored to specific market outlooks and volatility expectations. Common multi-leg strategies include:</p>

      <p><strong>Vertical Spreads:</strong> Involves buying and selling options of the same type (calls or puts) and expiration, but at different strike prices. Examples include Bull Call Spreads and Bear Put Spreads. These strategies define both maximum profit and maximum loss, making them highly efficient for directional trading with limited risk.</p>

      <p><strong>Iron Condors:</strong> A four-leg strategy consisting of a bear call spread and a bull put spread. It is a neutral strategy designed to profit from low volatility, where the trader expects the underlying stock to remain within a specific price range through expiration.</p>

      <p><strong>Straddles and Strangles:</strong> These strategies involve buying both a call and a put. A straddle uses the same strike price, while a strangle uses different strike prices (typically out-of-the-money). They are directionally neutral but require a significant move in the underlying asset's price to overcome the combined premium paid.</p>

      <h3>Key Metrics Explained</h3>
      <p>The calculator outputs several crucial metrics essential for evaluating a trade's viability:</p>
      <p><strong>Maximum Profit:</strong> The highest possible return the strategy can generate at expiration. For strategies involving long calls, this can be theoretically infinite. For credit spreads, it is capped at the net premium received.</p>
      <p><strong>Maximum Loss:</strong> The worst-case scenario. For long options or debit spreads, this is typically the total premium paid. For naked short calls, it is theoretically unlimited.</p>
      <p><strong>Break-even Points:</strong> The exact underlying price(s) at which the net P&L is exactly zero. Complex strategies like Iron Condors will have two break-even points, creating a profitable range.</p>
      <p><strong>Net Premium:</strong> The initial cash outlay or credit. A net debit means you are paying to enter the trade, while a net credit means cash is deposited into your account upon execution.</p>

      <p>By thoroughly modeling these parameters before execution, options traders can ensure their strategies align with their market thesis and risk management protocols.</p>
    </div>

    <section class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details>
        <summary>How do you calculate profit on an options call?</summary>
        <p>For a long call option, your profit at expiration is calculated by taking the underlying stock price, subtracting the strike price, and then subtracting the premium paid. Multiply this result by 100 per contract. If the stock price is below the strike price, your loss is capped at the premium paid.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>How do you use an options profit calculator?</summary>
        <p>To use an options profit calculator, enter your option's strike price, the premium paid (or received), the expiration date, and the number of contracts. The calculator will automatically generate a payoff diagram showing your break-even point, maximum profit, and maximum loss.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What is a good payoff for options?</summary>
        <p>A good payoff for options depends on your risk tolerance and strategy. Many traders look for a risk-to-reward ratio of at least 1:2 or 1:3, meaning they aim to make $2 or $3 for every $1 they risk. For selling options, a good payoff might mean consistently collecting premium with a high probability of success.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>How do you calculate break even on a put option?</summary>
        <p>To calculate the break-even point for a long put option, subtract the premium paid from the strike price. For a short put option (selling a put), the break-even point is also the strike price minus the premium received.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Can you lose more than you invest in options?</summary>
        <p>Yes, but it depends on the strategy. If you buy options (long calls or long puts), your maximum loss is strictly limited to the premium paid. However, if you sell naked options (short calls or short puts), your risk can be substantial, and in the case of naked short calls, theoretically unlimited.</p>
      </details>
    </section>
  </div>

  <script is:inline src="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/chart.js"></script>
  <script is:inline>
    document.addEventListener("DOMContentLoaded", function() {
      const legsContainer = document.getElementById('legs-container');
      const addLegBtn = document.getElementById('add-leg-btn');
      let legCount = 0;
      let payoffChart = null;

      function createLegHTML(id) {
        return `
          <div class="leg-item" id="leg-${id}">
            <div class="leg-header">
              <strong>Leg ${id}</strong>
              ${id > 1 ? `<button class="btn-remove" onclick="removeLeg(${id})">Remove</button>` : ''}
            </div>
            <div class="input-grid">
              <div>
                <label>Action</label>
                <select id="action-${id}" class="leg-input">
                  <option value="buy">Buy</option>
                  <option value="sell">Sell</option>
                </select>
              </div>
              <div>
                <label>Type</label>
                <select id="type-${id}" class="leg-input">
                  <option value="call">Call</option>
                  <option value="put">Put</option>
                </select>
              </div>
              <div>
                <label>Strike</label>
                <input type="number" step="0.5" id="strike-${id}" class="leg-input" value="${id === 1 ? 100 : 105}">
              </div>
              <div>
                <label>Premium</label>
                <input type="number" step="0.01" id="premium-${id}" class="leg-input" value="${id === 1 ? 2.50 : 1.00}">
              </div>
              <div>
                <label>Contracts</label>
                <input type="number" step="1" min="1" id="contracts-${id}" class="leg-input" value="1">
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        `;
      }

      window.removeLeg = function(id) {
        const el = document.getElementById(`leg-${id}`);
        if (el) el.remove();
        calculateAll();
      }

      function addLeg() {
        legCount++;
        const div = document.createElement('div');
        div.innerHTML = createLegHTML(legCount);
        legsContainer.appendChild(div.firstElementChild);

        // Add event listeners to new inputs
        document.querySelectorAll(`#leg-${legCount} .leg-input`).forEach(input => {
          input.addEventListener('input', calculateAll);
          input.addEventListener('change', calculateAll);
        });

        calculateAll();
      }

      function getLegs() {
        const legs = [];
        document.querySelectorAll('.leg-item').forEach(legEl => {
          const idStr = legEl.id.split('-')[1];
          legs.push({
            action: document.getElementById(`action-${idStr}`).value,
            type: document.getElementById(`type-${idStr}`).value,
            strike: parseFloat(document.getElementById(`strike-${idStr}`).value) || 0,
            premium: parseFloat(document.getElementById(`premium-${idStr}`).value) || 0,
            contracts: parseInt(document.getElementById(`contracts-${idStr}`).value) || 1
          });
        });
        return legs;
      }

      function calculatePayoff(underlyingPrice, legs) {
        let totalPnl = 0;
        legs.forEach(leg => {
          let legPnl = 0;
          const multiplier = 100 * leg.contracts;
          if (leg.type === 'call') {
            const intrinsic = Math.max(0, underlyingPrice - leg.strike);
            legPnl = leg.action === 'buy' ? (intrinsic - leg.premium) * multiplier : (leg.premium - intrinsic) * multiplier;
          } else {
            const intrinsic = Math.max(0, leg.strike - underlyingPrice);
            legPnl = leg.action === 'buy' ? (intrinsic - leg.premium) * multiplier : (leg.premium - intrinsic) * multiplier;
          }
          totalPnl += legPnl;
        });
        return totalPnl;
      }

      function formatCurrency(val) {
        return new Intl.NumberFormat('en-US', { style: 'currency', currency: 'USD' }).format(val);
      }

      function updateChart(labels, data, start, end) {
        const ctx = document.getElementById('payoffChart').getContext('2d');
        if (payoffChart) payoffChart.destroy();

        const pointColors = data.map(val => val >= 0 ? '#27ae60' : '#e74c3c');

        payoffChart = new Chart(ctx, {
          type: 'line',
          data: {
            labels: labels,
            datasets: [{
              label: 'Profit/Loss ($)',
              data: data,
              borderColor: '#4a8fe7',
              borderWidth: 2,
              pointBackgroundColor: pointColors,
              pointBorderColor: pointColors,
              pointRadius: 0,
              pointHoverRadius: 6,
              fill: {
                target: 'origin',
                above: 'rgba(39, 174, 96, 0.2)',
                below: 'rgba(231, 76, 60, 0.2)'
              }
            }]
          },
          options: {
            responsive: true,
            maintainAspectRatio: false,
            interaction: { intersect: false, mode: 'index' },
            plugins: { legend: { display: false } },
            scales: {
              x: { grid: { color: 'rgba(255,255,255,0.05)' }, ticks: { maxTicksLimit: 10 } },
              y: { grid: { color: 'rgba(255,255,255,0.05)', zeroLineColor: '#4a8fe7' } }
            }
          }
        });
      }

      function updateTable(legs, minStrike, maxStrike, maxLoss) {
        const tbody = document.getElementById('pnl-tbody');
        tbody.innerHTML = '';
        const range = maxStrike - minStrike;
        const step = Math.max(1, Math.round(range / 10));
        let pricesToTable = [];

        for(let i = minStrike - (step * 3); i <= maxStrike + (step * 3); i += step) {
          if (i > 0) pricesToTable.push(i);
        }
        legs.forEach(l => { if (!pricesToTable.includes(l.strike)) pricesToTable.push(l.strike); });

        pricesToTable.sort((a,b) => a - b);
        pricesToTable = pricesToTable.filter((item, pos, ary) => !pos || item !== ary[pos - 1]);
        const maxRisk = Math.abs(maxLoss);

        pricesToTable.forEach(p => {
          const pnl = calculatePayoff(p, legs);
          const tr = document.createElement('tr');
          const pnlClass = pnl > 0 ? 'text-green' : (pnl < 0 ? 'text-red' : '');
          const ror = maxRisk > 0 && maxRisk !== Infinity ? ((pnl / maxRisk) * 100).toFixed(1) + '%' : '--';

          tr.innerHTML = `
            <td>$${p.toFixed(2)}</td>
            <td class="${pnlClass}">${formatCurrency(pnl)}</td>
            <td class="${pnlClass}">${ror}</td>
          `;
          tbody.appendChild(tr);
        });
      }

      function calculateAll() {
        const legs = getLegs();
        if (legs.length === 0) return;

        const strikes = legs.map(l => l.strike);
        const minStrike = Math.min(...strikes);
        const maxStrike = Math.max(...strikes);
        const rangeMargin = Math.max(20, (maxStrike - minStrike) * 1.5);

        const startPrice = Math.max(0, minStrike - rangeMargin);
        const endPrice = maxStrike + rangeMargin;
        const step = (endPrice - startPrice) / 100;

        const labels = [];
        const data = [];
        let hasInfiniteProfit = false;
        let hasInfiniteLoss = false;

        for (let p = startPrice; p <= endPrice; p += step) {
          labels.push(p.toFixed(2));
          data.push(calculatePayoff(p, legs));
        }

        const lowestPricePnl = calculatePayoff(0, legs);
        const highestPricePnl = calculatePayoff(endPrice * 2, legs);

        if (highestPricePnl > data[data.length-1] && highestPricePnl > 1000000) hasInfiniteProfit = true;
        if (highestPricePnl < data[data.length-1] && highestPricePnl < -1000000) hasInfiniteLoss = true;

        let maxProfit = Math.max(...data);
        let maxLoss = Math.min(...data);

        const breakEvens = [];
        for (let i = 1; i < data.length; i++) {
          if ((data[i-1] <= 0 && data[i] > 0) || (data[i-1] >= 0 && data[i] < 0)) {
            const p1 = parseFloat(labels[i-1]);
            const p2 = parseFloat(labels[i]);
            const v1 = data[i-1];
            const v2 = data[i];
            const fraction = Math.abs(v1) / (Math.abs(v1) + Math.abs(v2));
            const be = p1 + fraction * (p2 - p1);
            if (!breakEvens.find(b => Math.abs(b - be) < 0.1)) breakEvens.push(be);
          }
        }

        let netPremium = 0;
        legs.forEach(leg => {
          const val = leg.premium * 100 * leg.contracts;
          if (leg.action === 'buy') netPremium -= val;
          else netPremium += val;
        });

        document.getElementById('stat-max-profit').innerText = hasInfiniteProfit ? 'Unlimited' : formatCurrency(maxProfit);
        document.getElementById('stat-max-profit').className = hasInfiniteProfit || maxProfit > 0 ? 'stat-value text-green' : 'stat-value';

        document.getElementById('stat-max-loss').innerText = hasInfiniteLoss ? 'Unlimited' : formatCurrency(maxLoss);
        document.getElementById('stat-max-loss').className = hasInfiniteLoss || maxLoss < 0 ? 'stat-value text-red' : 'stat-value';

        document.getElementById('stat-break-even').innerText = breakEvens.length > 0 ? breakEvens.map(b => `$${b.toFixed(2)}`).join(', ') : 'None';

        const npEl = document.getElementById('stat-net-premium');
        if (netPremium > 0) {
          npEl.innerText = `${formatCurrency(netPremium)} Credit`;
          npEl.className = 'stat-value text-green';
        } else if (netPremium < 0) {
          npEl.innerText = `${formatCurrency(Math.abs(netPremium))} Debit`;
          npEl.className = 'stat-value text-red';
        } else {
          npEl.innerText = '$0.00';
          npEl.className = 'stat-value';
        }

        updateChart(labels, data, startPrice, endPrice);
        updateTable(legs, minStrike, maxStrike, maxLoss);
      }

      addLegBtn.addEventListener('click', addLeg);

      // Init with default leg
      addLeg();
    });
  </script>

  <style is:inline>
    .page-content { max-width: 1000px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 2rem 1.5rem; }
    .hero { text-align: center; padding: 3rem 0 2rem; }
    .hero h1 { font-size: 2.5rem; font-weight: 800; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }
    .subtitle { color: var(--text-secondary); font-size: 1.1rem; max-width: 700px; margin: 0 auto; }

    .calculator-container { margin: 2rem 0; }
    .calculator-grid { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1.5fr; gap: 2rem; }
    @media (max-width: 768px) { .calculator-grid { grid-template-columns: 1fr; } }

    .calc-panel { background: var(--card-bg); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 12px; padding: 1.5rem; }

    .leg-item { background: rgba(0,0,0,0.2); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); padding: 1rem; border-radius: 8px; margin-bottom: 1rem; }
    .leg-header { display: flex; justify-content: space-between; align-items: center; margin-bottom: 1rem; font-weight: 600; }

    .input-grid { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 1rem; }
    .input-grid > div:last-child { grid-column: span 2; }

    label { display: block; font-size: 0.85rem; color: var(--text-secondary); margin-bottom: 0.25rem; }
    input, select { background: var(--bg-color); color: var(--text-primary); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); padding: 0.5rem; border-radius: 6px; width: 100%; font-size: 0.95rem; }
    input:focus, select:focus { outline: none; border-color: var(--accent-color); }

    .btn-secondary { background: transparent; color: var(--accent-color); border: 1px solid var(--accent-color); padding: 0.5rem 1rem; border-radius: 6px; cursor: pointer; width: 100%; font-weight: 600; }
    .btn-secondary:hover { background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--accent-color) 10%, transparent); }
    .btn-remove { background: transparent; color: #ef4444; border: none; cursor: pointer; font-size: 0.85rem; }
    .btn-remove:hover { text-decoration: underline; }

    .stats-grid { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 1rem; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; }
    .stat-box { background: rgba(0,0,0,0.2); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 8px; padding: 1rem; text-align: center; }
    .stat-label { font-size: 0.85rem; color: var(--text-secondary); text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.5px; }
    .stat-value { font-size: 1.25rem; font-weight: 700; margin-top: 0.25rem; }
    .break-even-val { font-size: 1.1rem; }

    .text-green { color: #10b981 !important; }
    .text-red { color: #ef4444 !important; }

    .chart-wrapper { height: 300px; width: 100%; margin: 1.5rem 0; }

    .table-container { overflow-x: auto; }
    table { width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 0.9rem; }
    th, td { padding: 0.75rem; text-align: right; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-color); }
    th { color: var(--text-secondary); font-weight: 600; }
    th:first-child, td:first-child { text-align: left; }

    .explainer { margin-top: 3rem; }
    .explainer h2, .explainer h3 { margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 1rem; }
    .explainer p { margin-bottom: 1rem; color: var(--text-secondary); line-height: 1.7; }
    .explainer ul { margin-bottom: 1.5rem; padding-left: 1.5rem; color: var(--text-secondary); }
    .explainer li { margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }
    .explainer a { color: var(--accent-color); text-decoration: none; }
    .explainer a:hover { text-decoration: underline; }

    .faq-section { margin-top: 3rem; }
    .faq-section details { margin: 1rem 0; padding: 1rem; background: var(--card-bg); border-radius: 8px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); }
    .faq-section summary { font-weight: 600; cursor: pointer; }
    .faq-section p { margin-top: 1rem; color: var(--text-secondary); }
  </style>
</SiteLayout>
